answer.en:
### Singleton Pattern

Singleton ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global access point. Use it when you need lazy initialization, control over instantiation timing, or need to prevent multiple instances at runtime.

```typescript
class DatabaseConnection {
  private static instance: DatabaseConnection;
  private constructor() {}

  static getInstance(): DatabaseConnection {
    if (!this.instance) {
      this.instance = new DatabaseConnection();
    }
    return this.instance;
  }
}

const db1 = DatabaseConnection.getInstance();
const db2 = DatabaseConnection.getInstance();
console.log(db1 === db2); // true
```

**Common interview trap:** Confusing Singleton with a module export—ES6 modules are already singletons, so true Singleton is rarely needed in modern JavaScript.

