### Factory Pattern

Factory provides a method to create objects without specifying exact classes. It encapsulates object creation logic and allows runtime selection of the type. Abstract Factory creates families of related objects, while Factory creates individual types.

```typescript
interface Notification {
  send(message: string): void;
}
class EmailNotification implements Notification {
  send(msg: string) { console.log(`Email: ${msg}`); }
}
class SMSNotification implements Notification {
  send(msg: string) { console.log(`SMS: ${msg}`); }
}

class NotificationFactory {
  static create(type: string): Notification {
    if (type === 'email') return new EmailNotification();
    if (type === 'sms') return new SMSNotification();
    throw new Error('Unknown type');
  }
}
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking Factory and Abstract Factory are the same—Abstract Factory creates multiple related product families.

