answer.en:
### Abstract Factory Pattern

Abstract Factory creates families of related objects (e.g., entire UI theme with button, input, dialog). Use it when you need to swap entire product families at runtime. Choose it over Factory when products are interdependent and must work together.

```typescript
interface Theme { button(): Button; input(): Input; }
interface Button { render(): string; }
interface Input { render(): string; }

class LightButton implements Button { render() { return 'Light Button'; } }
class DarkButton implements Button { render() { return 'Dark Button'; } }

class LightTheme implements Theme {
  button() { return new LightButton(); }
  input() { return new LightInput(); }
}

const theme: Theme = new LightTheme();
theme.button().render();
```

**Common interview trap:** Overusing Abstract Factory for unrelated objects—it's only beneficial when products form a cohesive family.

