answer.en:
### Builder Pattern

Builder separates object construction from its representation, allowing step-by-step assembly of complex objects with many optional parameters. Use it instead of Factory when you have numerous optional fields and need readable construction chains.

```typescript
class RequestBuilder {
  private url: string = '';
  private method: string = 'GET';
  private headers: Record<string, string> = {};

  setUrl(url: string) { this.url = url; return this; }
  setMethod(method: string) { this.method = method; return this; }
  addHeader(key: string, value: string) { this.headers[key] = value; return this; }
  build() { return { url: this.url, method: this.method, headers: this.headers }; }
}

const req = new RequestBuilder().setUrl('/api').setMethod('POST').addHeader('Auth', 'token').build();
```

**Common interview trap:** Using Builder for objects with few fields—it adds complexity without benefit; use constructors or Factory instead.

