### Prototype Pattern

Prototype creates new objects by cloning an existing object instead of instantiating from scratch. Use it when object creation is expensive or when you need independent copies with nested structures. Object.assign() creates shallow copies; Prototype requires deep cloning for nested objects.

```typescript
interface Cloneable {
  clone(): Cloneable;
}
class User implements Cloneable {
  constructor(public name: string, public address: { city: string }) {}
  clone(): User {
    return new User(this.name, JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(this.address)));
  }
}

const user1 = new User('John', { city: 'NYC' });
const user2 = user1.clone();
user2.address.city = 'LA';
console.log(user1.address.city); // 'NYC' - independent copy
```

**Common interview trap:** Using Object.assign() for deep cloning—it only copies top-level properties; nested objects remain referenced.

