### Singleton vs Builder

Singleton ensures one global instance (e.g., logger, config), while Builder constructs complex objects step-by-step. Use Singleton for stateless shared resources; use Builder when you need flexible, multi-step construction with optional parameters.

```typescript
// Singleton - single global instance
class Logger {
  private static instance: Logger;
  private constructor() {}
  static getInstance() {
    return this.instance ??= new Logger();
  }
}

// Builder - flexible construction
class ConfigBuilder {
  private config = {};
  setDatabase(db: string) { this.config.db = db; return this; }
  setPort(port: number) { this.config.port = port; return this; }
  build() { return this.config; }
}
```

**Common interview trap:** Using Singleton for everything with configuration — this breaks testability; Builder is better for mutable config objects.

